WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.372
The periodic table is not a colourful wall poster invented
to frighten classrooms. It is a map of the element types.

2
00:00:07.372 --> 00:00:11.979
Each tile says: here is one kind of atom that nature can
use.

3
00:00:11.979 --> 00:00:19.924
Hydrogen is H. Oxygen is O. Carbon is C. Copper is Cu.
Iron is Fe. Gold is Au.

4
00:00:19.924 --> 00:00:26.948
Some symbols are obvious. C for carbon is friendly. O for
oxygen is practically waving.

5
00:00:26.948 --> 00:00:38.219
Some are older-name surprises. Iron is Fe from ferrum.
Copper is Cu from cuprum. Gold is Au from aurum. Chemistry
has history tucked inside its labels.

6
00:00:38.219 --> 00:00:43.884
You do not need to memorise the whole table today. But you
should know what the table is doing.

7
00:00:43.884 --> 00:00:55.055
Each element has a position. The position is not random.
The table is arranged by atomic number. For this course,
think of atomic number as the element's address on the

8
00:00:55.055 --> 00:01:04.910
Hydrogen is number one. Helium is number two. Carbon is
six. Oxygen is eight. Copper is twenty-nine. Gold is
seventy-nine.

9
00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:13.237
The table also shows patterns. Many metals live across the
left and middle. Non-metals sit mostly toward the right.

10
00:01:13.237 --> 00:01:22.937
Columns are called groups. Elements in the same group
often behave in related ways. Rows are called periods.
They show the order across the map.

11
00:01:22.937 --> 00:01:33.779
Try reading the map like a chemist. A tile gives you the
symbol, the name, and the address number. It is not asking
you to panic; it is giving you coordinates.

12
00:01:33.779 --> 00:01:46.198
If the control room lights up C, think carbon: graphite in
pencil, diamond, and lots of living things. If it lights
up O, think oxygen: air, water, and many compounds.

13
00:01:46.198 --> 00:01:56.736
If it lights up Fe, think iron: nails, tools, and rust
problems. If it lights up Cu, think copper: wires, coins,
and that warm orange-brown metal colour.

14
00:01:56.736 --> 00:02:10.233
Now compare two tiles. Carbon and oxygen have different
symbols and different atomic numbers, so they are
different element types. A carbon atom does not become

15
00:02:10.233 --> 00:02:22.346
That is why labels matter. In a particle diagram, two
circles can look similar, but C and O tell you they are
different atoms. The periodic table is the label key for

16
00:02:22.346 --> 00:02:35.506
The table also helps avoid a common mistake. Water is not
on the periodic table because water is not an element. It
is made from elements. The table lists the building

17
00:02:35.506 --> 00:02:48.456
Try this quick read: Na and Cl are element symbols. Sodium
chloride, table salt, is not a new periodic-table tile. It
is a compound made using element types from the table.

18
00:02:48.456 --> 00:02:56.095
We are not doing electron shells today. The big idea is
enough: the periodic table is a map, not a memory
punishment.

19
00:02:56.095 --> 00:03:06.219
When you see Cu on a coin or Fe on a lab card, think: atom
type. When you see the whole table, think: organised map
of elements.
